@@eThe Scorched Wastes -- Wall Command Threat Lecture@@N

Wall Command instructors use the Scorched Wastes as a teaching
horror. Not because the Wastes threaten Kiess directly -- they are
far to the east, beyond Midgaard's reach -- but because they
demonstrate the @@rfinal stage@@N of what Kiess was founded to prevent.

The Wastes were once the @@yMeridian Intake March@@N: a managed corridor
of toll pavilions, cistern regulators, and charter stations. Orderly.
Functional. Governed. Then the @@rNinth Meridian Rite@@N failed, heat
surged through channels meant for water, and the corridor burned.
That is catastrophe. What came @@rafter@@N is the true nightmare.

The @@yCharter Remnants@@N are the detail that makes new Wall Command
recruits go quiet. Some are living survivalists descended from
intake clerks. Others are @@rundead functionaries@@N -- revenants of
ration auditors and checkpoint officials who still demand documents,
still issue citations, still @@rattack when proper paperwork is not
produced@@N. Administrative process persisting after every legitimate
authority has died. This is what a @@rsealed warrant@@N looks like when
it outlives not just its signatories but its entire civilization.

The @@rDune Host Reavers@@N inherited route knowledge from ruined intake
records and hoard water containers and legal tablets equally. The
@@dSynod Eclipse Cells@@N recut old inscriptions, stage mock tribunals,
and conduct witness-burning rites, convinced that the failed
synthesis can be corrected. Every faction in the Wastes performs
the @@yforms@@N of governance without any of its substance.

The @@yTrade Syndics@@N extract a commercial lesson: verdict halls
inhabited by revenants, toll stones recut as curses, ration seals
worn by raiders. @@yLaw persists after legitimacy dies.@@N When the
tools of administration survive the administrators, they do not go
dormant. They become weapons.

Kiess's founding clause -- @@y"No sealed warrant from a predecessor
authority shall bind a Kiess citizen"@@N -- was written because of
Evermeet's obsidian disc. But the Wastes prove the principle holds
universally. Every sealed document, every emergency power without
sunset, every toll right without renewal -- all of them tend toward
the same destination: @@rundead process governing living people@@N.

@@dWall Command@@N ends the lecture with a standing question posted on
the briefing board: @@r"If Kiess fell tomorrow, which of our orders
would keep executing without us?"@@N

The answer is supposed to be none. The question is whether that
remains true.
